          explanation: 'Causal inference requires: temporal precedence (cause precedes effect), covariation, and elimination of alternative explanations. A longitudinal cohort study measures discrimination at time 1 and allostatic load at later time points, establishing temporal order. Repeated biomarker measurements capture biological accumulation over time. Statistical adjustment for confounders (SES, lifestyle factors) addresses alternative explanations. Cross-sectional (A) cannot establish temporal precedence. National mortality data (B) does not measure individual discrimination experiences. An experimental RCT (D) exposing people to discrimination would be deeply unethical.',
